<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If they have more fun doing something that aims at different goals, it's their choice and since they're having fun, where's the damage? - Mystic<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Do you honestly believe that for 60+ Wizards that getting GSS is not a goal?  The choice is not theirs, it is their guild's as a whole.  What Magician would chose not to get Firebolt of Talon?  What are the consequences of his decision?  The only decision that is likely to affect acquisition of GSS, is which guild they can reasonably become a member of.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And saying that family type guilds can't go to VT is so false. It's like saying family type guilds don't kill Nagafen. While both are true in some point in time, in the end they're not. Eventually emperor of ssra and VT will be playing grounds of family type guilds, and on BB they are to some extend. The guilds doing VT at the moment aren't what you (or anyone) would classify as uber guilds. - Mystic<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It really depends on what your definition of a family guild is.  I think many believe this to be a guild which allow choices among its members, as apposed to a full time raiding guild with mandatory objectives and play/level requirements.   Sure a high end guild can have a family atmosphere but this is not the same as a casual raiding guild with few requirements other than mutual respect of its members.<br>
<br>
Comparing the trivialization of Nagafen to the Emperor Ssra is beyond preposterous.  No single group is going to take down the Emperor anywhere in the near future, unless the next couple of expansions expand levels again, and the game totally deteriorates.  In any case the event is not in the foreseeable future.  I doubt that anyone will ever solo the Emperor Ssra.  The two jumps in power are not even close to comparable.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>How about the wizards without AA crits and mage without AA crits... who's going to crit more? - Mystic<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
They wizard for maybe a little less than 2% of the time and for up to 55% additional damage.  This appears to have a net difference of around 1%.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But even with the AA's maxed, if wizards get the 22% crit rate people on these boards claim, do mages get that with their AA crits maxed? Or do they get somewhere around 10%? Any mage to post log information and rates? - Mystic<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I have never read a post where a wizard claimed to have a 22% crit rate over a sustained period of time.  The posts I have read indicated that the crit rate was around 19% with maxed AA crits plus innate crits.  On the Magician board they are saying that with PoP crits they are getting around 12% crit rate.  AA crits give roughly 2% per level the wizard gets 3 levels + innate and the Magician 2 levels.  Even when you use your numbers, how do you get 3x when you calculate 22/10, like I said your statement was blatantly false.  PoP AA reduced the margin between our crit percentages bringing the magician abilities closer to ours in this area.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But to say my guild carried me through these encounters is a bit harsh. Guild killing stuff is team effort and while single person is contributing less to the kill than he/she is while soloing, it is often still needed. - Mystic<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't think it is harsh compared to your 'choice' theory.  If we were to switch guilds, I would have GSS and you would not.  I met a 62 wizard that had GSS from a high end guild who did not even know what SCS was.  She chose to use it in PoV over DoR in the desert, but then she had the option of being in a full time raiding guild where I could not play at their raid start time, nor as often as they required.  Of course she didn't know where the HoH camp in PoV was either.  The only 'choice' she could make that would affect her acquisition of the spell was which guild she should join.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It is all about preferences and goals, if the goals aren't towards the rewards you want, maybe it is time to readjust your goals? - Mystic<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No it is not about individual goals but it is about guild capabilities and goals, or incredible sums of plat if these start showing up in the bazaar.  I finally found Sunstrike for sale in the bazaar for the measly sum of 70k, SoS was 190K.  Both were gone by the time I checked later (not that I would pay 70k for SS, nor could I afford SoS).  I have never seen GSS or EER for sale in the bazaar, but your mileage my vary.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Gwideon, I understand the want for store bought big nuke at 61, just to compensate the feelings of some wizards against 62nd level mages who have AA crits. But I don't see the need for it. - Mystic<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Since anyone can see spell damage now, crits are not necessary to show the gap between our spells.  And a mage only has to be 61 to purchase FoT for pocket change.  You will not see it because you are trying your utmost not to.  As far as your explanation of why you didn't think my suggestion was valid.... well you didn't give one.<br>
<br>
Gwideon<br>
PHENOMENAL COSMIC POWER!<br>
in an itty bitty living space<br>
