<br>
And that pretty much sums up what my definition of a family guild is. No steady raid times in a sense of 4+ times/week, no requirements for playtime, etc. Level requirements come by nature, as it is often so that guilds filled with 55th level people will not recruit 10th level character even though they say they don't have level requirements.<br>
<br>
Yet there are people in such guilds who have SS, GSS, EER, SoS, etc. Although people in this board make it sound impossible.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Comparing the trivialization of Nagafen to the Emperor Ssra is beyond preposterous. No single group is going to take down the Emperor anywhere in the near future, unless the next couple of expansions expand levels again, and the game totally deteriorates. In any case the event is not in the foreseeable future. I doubt that anyone will ever solo the Emperor Ssra. The two jumps in power are not even close to comparable.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I remember when people said no one will take down Nagafen with single group in any foreseeable future, yet it would be way easy to do nowadays. Unless you're privy to some secret dev information, the foreseeable future can hold anything for us. I also remember when people posted that only ubers will ever get to VP, ST... yet, those are playgrounds of family guilds nowadays. Same will happen to ssra/vt, whether you want to believe it or not.<br>
<br>
So where's the preposterous comparison? EQ has changed, most of Luclin was first done by ubers with 60+ people... yet in the end it dropped down to 20sh people. First Ghould Lords in LGuk were done with 2 groups, and it soon dropped down to soloing. First Nagafens took 40+ people and deaths and bind rushing, but in the end they were done with lot less. EVERYTHING in EQ is getting killed with less and less people and less and less timesinks as time goes by. If you don't want to believe that, it is your choice.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I have never read a post where a wizard claimed to have a 22% crit rate over a sustained period of time. The posts I have read indicated that the crit rate was around 19% with maxed AA crits plus innate crits. On the Magician board they are saying that with PoP crits they are getting around 12% crit rate. AA crits give roughly 2% per level the wizard gets 3 levels + innate and the Magician 2 levels. Even when you use your numbers, how do you get 3x when you calculate 22/10, like I said your statement was blatantly false. PoP AA reduced the margin between our crit percentages bringing the magician abilities closer to ours in this area.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Maybe, just maybe.. you might want to read the sticky in General board titled &quot;Wizard Mini-FAQ&quot; where it states that with maxed AA crits you'll get 20% (+2% from innate) crit rate. And that's supposedly verified by tons of wizards.<br>
<br>
3x came from thin air, like I said, I don't know mage crit rates. And can you even max the PoP crits at level 62? Or is the magician at 62 level with maxed crits a blatantly false too?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I don't think it is harsh compared to your 'choice' theory. If we were to switch guilds, I would have GSS and you would not. I met a 62 wizard that had GSS from a high end guild who did not even know what SCS was. She chose to use it in PoV over DoR in the desert, but then she had the option of being in a full time raiding guild where I could not play at their raid start time, nor as often as they required. Of course she didn't know where the HoH camp in PoV was either. The only 'choice' she could make that would affect her acquisition of the spell was which guild she should join.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If we were to switch guilds, I probably wouldn't stay at the guild you're in but change to one that suits my goals in game and reflects my playstyle. And on the other hand, you'd be kicked out because of attendance and wouldn't have GSS. The game gives what you put in. And... I don't know where HoH camp in PoV is, yet I know tons where what is in PoTime... then again I also know where matriarch and patriarch camps are in Kedge. What does knowing PoV has to do with anything?<br>
<br>
The choice she made was to set goals to get the spells and join a team that can take her there. There are other routes too, making friends and raiding with people who keel what you want while being in a family guild is always an option... most people just choose not to utilize it. OR they aren't nice, friendly, whatnot and can't make friends... I don't know the drivers different people have, but I do know that people who put in the time/effort, get what they want from the game, unless they're total jerks.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>No it is not about individual goals but it is about guild capabilities and goals, or incredible sums of plat if these start showing up in the bazaar. I finally found Sunstrike for sale in the bazaar for the measly sum of 70k, SoS was 190K. Both were gone by the time I checked later (not that I would pay 70k for SS, nor could I afford SoS). I have never seen GSS or EER for sale in the bazaar, but your mileage my vary.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Individual goals and drivers get people to join guilds and make friends... they also get people to raid with friends and guilds and keel targets. Guild doesn't have a mind, it is a team made of individuals. Some individuals have goals that make them change guilds every couple of months... some individuals have goals to be master in all tradeskills, some couldn't care less about tradeskills. Some individuals have goals to see PoTime, while others couldn't care less about that. The biggest problem is the old phrase &quot;I pay same amount, I am entitled to get everything too&quot;. People just don't realize that everyone has the same chance in game, but it is up to the individuals if they can/will take up on it. Some people can play 60 hours a week, some can play 2 hours a week. And the rewards will be different, but maybe it should be printed on the box so people would know it before buying.<br>
<br>
Sunstrike was sub-30k on BB while PoP was still unannounced. EER and GSS have both been seen in bazaar quite few times. So yes, my mileage varies from yours quite a bit. And making plat is the easiest thing to do in EQ, at one point I had a bit over 500k without any uberloots or phatgear to sell / auction. Saving up and just fooling around stacked up eventually.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Since anyone can see spell damage now, crits are not necessary to show the gap between our spells. And a mage only has to be 61 to purchase FoT for pocket change. You will not see it because you are trying your utmost not to. As far as your explanation of why you didn't think my suggestion was valid.... well you didn't give one.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Because there isn't valid basis for the suggestion. It is like Qaman's suggestion of giving FD to wizards because some people would like it. The spell you described is not needed, by any means. Sure some people want it, but then again, AE DT would be fun spell to have too.<br>
<br>
Like I said, they should first correct the problem at level 34 spells before concentrating on 60+, because majority of wizards will hit lvl 34 compared to hitting lvls 60+. And as they haven't 'corrected' the problem with dd vs bolt that has been damagewise there for 4+ years... why do you see the need for them to fix similar situation at level 60+?<br>
<br>
-myz <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gwideonthegnome>GwideonTheGnome</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 146<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/19/03 5:50 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: back yet?</span><hr size=1> Gnomish Greetings!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And that pretty much sums up what my definition of a family guild is. No steady raid times in a sense of 4+ times/week, no requirements for playtime, etc. Level requirements come by nature, as it is often so that guilds filled with 55th level people will not recruit 10th level character even though they say they don't have level requirements.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
So if our definitions are similar, you are saying that there are guilds successfully taking down the Emperor that have no level requirement to be 60+, who have an optional raiding schedule, and requires no minimum play time or raid attendance to join?  I am truly impressed that they can pull that off.  Which guilds are these?<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Yet there are people in such guilds who have SS, GSS, EER, SoS, etc. Although people in this board make it sound impossible.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Not impossible, but not equitable either.  When FoT is on a vendor for pocket change, GSS should not be that rare or hard to obtain.  <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I remember when people said no one will take down Nagafen with single group in any foreseeable future, yet it would be way easy to do nowadays. Unless you're privy to some secret dev information, the foreseeable future can hold anything for us. I also remember when people posted that only ubers will ever get to VP, ST... yet, those are playgrounds of family guilds nowadays. Same will happen to ssra/vt, whether you want to believe it or not.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
SoE has stated they are not planning on increasing level ranges in the next expansion.  With the Emperor being a longer encounter and the side rooms likely to repop during the fight, I think it is fairly safe to say that a single group will not take down the Emperor even with the next expansion.  Nagafen was taken down by a single group before Velious was released, and by some family guilds with around 10 members shortly after Velious release.  Nagafen and Vox were trivialized so much, they felt it necessary to put a level restriction on the encounter.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So where's the preposterous comparison?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
I guess SoE better get to work putting a max level requirement on Ssra mobs, because the encounter was trivialized by PoP.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Maybe, just maybe.. you might want to read the sticky in General board titled &quot;Wizard Mini-FAQ&quot; where it states that with maxed AA crits you'll get 20% (+2% from innate) crit rate. And that's supposedly verified by tons of wizards.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Zarbonius probably did not take into account that the original thread in the library was parsing all critical spells (including innate).  I dont think there is a parser available to most that differentiate an innate crit versus an AA crit.  A 22% total crit rate over any extended period of time has not to my knowledge ever been confirmed, although crit rates in general have been questioned multiple times.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>3x came from thin air, like I said, I don't know mage crit rates. And can you even max the PoP crits at level 62? Or is the magician at 62 level with maxed crits a blatantly false too?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
No you cannot max AA crits at 62.  Magicians should crit between 8  9% with FoM (since they were reporting 6-7% with SCF3), the wizard would be at about a 16-17% crit rate, still not close to 3x.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If we were to switch guilds, I probably wouldn't stay at the guild you're in but change to one that suits my goals in game and reflects my playstyle. And on the other hand, you'd be kicked out because of attendance and wouldn't have GSS.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
So at least you seem to acknowledge that guild membership plays a significant role in the ability to acquire this spell.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Because there isn't valid basis for the suggestion. It is like Qaman's suggestion of giving FD to wizards because some people would like it. The spell you described is not needed, by any means. Sure some people want it, but then again, AE DT would be fun spell to have too.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
There is a valid basis for the suggestion; we have provided a multitude of reasons with supporting arguments that the current situation is unbalanced.  Asking to have the situation looked at is not unreasonable.  SoE made a major fopaw when the put FoT on a vendor.  It shows you they had no idea how uncommon even Sunstrike was, much less how rare GSS was and continues to be.  Before you say that Sunstrike is not uncommon recognize that the spell would not be 30k even on your server if it was common.  Kunark dragons are taken down regularly on spawn, so those spells have to go somewhere.  Availability will determine price.<br>
