10 might be optimistic... can't say. Haven't been to there in 6+ months. But on the other hand, did tank Sontalak for 1.5 minutes today on my wiz. I think 18 or so is current 'low' number with which people have done emp ssra (I could be wrong) and we're still just starting to tap into high-end PoP-gear. Items with 200+ hp/mana will mean additional 75+ of both per slot compared to Luclin.<br>
<br>
Kunark gave us 10 levels, which took us 5 levels over Nag/Vox. In order to as strong level wise difference to happen, they need to up the levels to around 75 or 80 I guess. But they learned from Kunark and the rise in power has been more moderate since. I still don't understand what the 3 expansions are, because surely you're not calculating LoY as an expansion that affects it, when all it gave was pink trolls and bank slots. And was aimed to 35-60 crowd. In that sense, PoFear, PoHate, PoAir were 3 expansions before Kunark came out. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
And next expansion won't give us any rise in power, no levels, no aa, no nothing. Just few more zones to explore. So... emp ssra will probably stay as hard encounter for some people even after that. Looks like SOE is learning that rise in power isn't good for the game they created. They did it with Velious, but went South again with Luclin/PoP.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Of course I was being sarcastic, because the encounter was not gimped to the level of the original dragons as you implied. It was not status that lead to the restriction but monopolization of the spawns by small groups. A similar reason was given as part of why Manaburn was nerfed. It is true that no-one knows what future expansions may hold, but I can safely say that the Emperor Ssra is nowhere near a trivial encounter currently for the vast majority of players.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Matter of opinion... way I read it back then, the restriction came because Nag/Vox are 'first uber encounters for people to train on' and they wanted to keep it so. Sure they didn't like people duoing them, but the reason they posted back then (if I recall correctly) was the 'raid encounter experience'.<br>
<br>
Currently emp ssra isn't nowhere trivial to vast majority, but Nag/Vox wasn't either nowhere trivial for the vast majority when the restriction came about. For example content that I consider trivial, probably isn't so for vast majority of players.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Wizards were getting close to a 14% total crit rate at the end of Luclin which is where the original numbers for the library came from. If the trend your seeing is indicative of what others see over time then there must be other factors that contribute to crit rate. (ie level, size, stats, resists)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
My numbers come mainly from raid encounters (90/10 split) at higher end PoP.<br>
<br>
12148 casts of SoS/SoM/AT/ADoI/ISoS/DoR/DoE and 16.26% crit rate. SoS has lowest at 15.32 (3023) and ISoS has highest at 17.39 (2779).<br>
<br>
So, if magicians are getting 14% and wizards are getting 16%... the extra AA seem to be useless OR the magicians are exaggerating.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> A wizard should not have to be a higher level to be equitable in his own area of expertise, nor should another class be that close especially when they other means to reliably deliver damage. My concern is primarily in experience groups where the down sides of bolt play a much lesser role, and where wizards have had the most complaints.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Let me ask you this, since you're nearing 65th. Are you looking forward to SoS (reliable) or SoM (big damage)? Which means more to you?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Gave? Even Sunstrike takes considerable effort to acquire on my server. I know 2 60+ wizards in my guild who do not even have Sunstrike yet, it is not impossible to get, but we were not given the spell like our Magician friends were given Firebolt of Talon.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
My mistake, I thought mixed levels of FoT and DoR in my head.<br>
<br>
Anyway, they get a decent nuke at 61 and some wizards have similar at 60th, but newer / lazy wizards don't. You have to remember that some wizards got SS about 3 years ago. Anyway, even if wizard00 is so incapable of getting plat / friends that he/she doesn't have any of the 60th level nukes, he will still have the draughts. I don't know your server, but if killing emp in sebilis is considered a considerable effort, then I assume it is Stromm. But even for wizards who can't get any of the 60th spells, it is only one fast level to go for DoR.<br>
<br>
Also, people who rush through levels and don't gear up are going to be lacking in gear and people who farm gear may level slower but will get the gear. Getting SS at meaningful level is so easy even today, as you don't even need to be 60th to farm it.<br>
<br>
Let me spell it out, sounds like mountain out of molehill with FoT again.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> If you do not believe that availability is the primary driving force in this situation, you are delusional. If there is one person selling a useful item they can name their highest reasonable price, if there are 100 people offering the item the price would be driven down to what a merchant would pay. Diamonds are a good example of what availability can do to price. This is economics 101.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Highest reasonable price... which in BB can mean 400kpp, but on some newer server can mean 10kpp. Availability of merchandise isn't the only one determining the price, like I said. Please, take a moment to read, that is Written Comprehension 101 - Step 1. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Looks like this long thread can be summarized easily:<br>
Wizards-without-big-60th-nuke:&quot;FoT is unbalanced.&quot;<br>
Wizards-with-big-60th-nuke:&quot;FoT is just fine, we have better spells.&quot;<br>
<br>
